[1] Cholera - Congo DR (Sud-Kivu Province)
Date: Fri, 17 Feb 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: UN Mission in the Congo [edited]
<http://www.monuc.org/news.aspx?newsID=9981>

Almost 400 people are infected and 7 have died from cholera in a town
in eastern Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) with a shortage of
clean drinking water, health authorities said on Thu, 16 Feb 2006.
Dieudonne Kalumuna, a medical inspector in the DRC's Sud-Kivu
province, told AFP that 398 cases of cholera and 7 cholera-related
deaths had been recorded since the start of 2006 in Uvira, a town of
200 000 people. "The epidemic was growing in Uvira," where an average
of 7 cases of the disease are usually recorded every month, before
doctors began raising awareness among locals, he said. Doctors have
been able to slow down the spread of the disease by a campaign in
schools, churches and markets to teach hygiene rules, he added.
The renewed outbreak of cholera in Uvira risks being aggravated by a
recent disconnection of the water supply caused by an electricity
breakdown which has caused residents to take water from the
Tanganyika lake that lies next to the town. Such disconnections are
frequent in the town. 50 cases of cholera were also found in the
southern Sud-Kivu regions of Fizi, Ruzizi and Nundu. Kalumuna said
most cases usually occurred during the current rainy season.
--
