[5] Cholera - Mozambique (Central Provinces)
Date: Wed, 15 Feb 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and Agencia de Informacao de Mocambique [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200602150657.html>

2 more people died of cholera in the central Mozambican province of
Sofala over the last 2 days, bringing to 6 the total number of deaths
out of 1622 cases diagnosed in Sofala this year, reports Wednesday's
(15 Feb 2006) issue of the Maputo daily "Noticias".
Because of the seriousness of the situation, health officials at
central level met this week in Beira with representatives of NGOs,
religious leaders, political parties and traditional healers to
discuss ways to check the disease. The Health authorities said that,
of the 2 deaths, 1 occurred in Beira, and the other in Dondo, about
30 kilometres west of the provincial capital. The source said that
31 new cases were notified in the province during the last 48 hours,
11 of them in Beira, 4 in Nhamatanda, 14 in Dondo, and 1 each in the
districts of Buzi and Caia.
Beira had previously been reporting an average of 20 cases a day,
mainly from the neighborhoods of Munhava, Manga, Praia-Nova, and
Chipangara, because of the prevailing very poor sanitation conditions.
Cholera cases have also been reported in the neighboring provinces of
Zambezia and Manica. Zambezia diagnosed 2 new cases during the last 2
days in Namacurra district.
Since the start of 2006, Zambezia has notified a total of 161 cases,
39 of them in the provincial capital, Quelimane, 89 in the district
of Gile, 15 in Mopeia, and 18 in Namacurra.
As for Manica, the health authorities notified 1 new case, in
Chimoio, the capital, during the last 48 hours, thus bringing to 58
the total number of cases in 2006. 56 of these were in Chimoio, and
the other 2 in Manica town.
